          "body": "9:15-22 explains *why* a death was required. The author exploits the polysemy of *diathēkē* — both *covenant* (the Old Testament sense) and *last will and testament* (the Greco-Roman sense). A will takes effect only at the death of the testator (9:16-17). The Mosaic covenant itself was inaugurated with blood (9:18-22, recalling Exodus 24:3-8); Moses sprinkled the book and the people with blood and said *this is the blood of the covenant*. The summary axiom lands in 9:22: *without shedding of blood there is no forgiveness*. The principle is not arbitrary cruelty but covenant logic — promises that bind require a death to ratify them. Christ's death therefore is not a regrettable accident but the necessary ratification of the promised inheritance."
