          "body": "9:23-26 presses the necessity argument to its conclusion. If the copies needed cleansing with animal blood, the heavenly archetypes required better sacrifices. But here is the key — *better* does not mean *more of the same*. Christ does not enter often. He does not offer Himself year by year. Why? Because if He did, *He would have needed to suffer often since the foundation of the world* (9:26). The author's logic is brutal: repetition itself testifies to insufficiency. Every annual entrance of the Aaronic high priest was a confession that last year's entrance had not finished the job. Christ's *ephapax* — *once at the consummation of the ages* — is therefore not just historically singular but theologically necessary. A repeatable sacrifice could not save; a saving sacrifice cannot be repeated."
